WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.320
So, the first question that you may be asking in the audience today is, who am I?

00:00:11.320 --> 00:00:14.920
I am a marine community ecologist by training.

00:00:14.920 --> 00:00:21.080
I'm passionate about using math to understand natural systems and using RStudio to do it.

00:00:21.080 --> 00:00:26.480
My current work is looking at marine communities and how they're responding to climate change.

00:00:26.480 --> 00:00:31.200
And so, even though I'm battling a lot of imposter syndrome, to say this in front of

00:00:31.200 --> 00:00:36.880
the room full of incredible RStudio users in front of me today, I am a data scientist.

00:00:36.880 --> 00:00:43.560
Thank you.

00:00:43.560 --> 00:00:48.480
And as a data scientist and as a marine scientist, I'm very familiar with walking into rooms

00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:51.400
and being one of very few, if any.

00:00:51.400 --> 00:00:54.799
In fact, I'm one of the 3%.

00:00:54.799 --> 00:00:59.799
Data suggests that fewer than 3% of data scientists are women of color.

00:00:59.799 --> 00:01:06.599
And while I humbly stand before you all today, pronouncing this as a success story, there

00:01:06.599 --> 00:01:11.400
were a number of trials and tribulations along the way.

00:01:11.400 --> 00:01:15.800
And so, I want to talk a little bit about how I was almost lost on this journey to data

00:01:15.800 --> 00:01:21.279
science and how I almost was not standing in front of you all today giving this presentation.

00:01:21.279 --> 00:01:26.720
When I started graduate school, I felt like the corner of this photo, of this beautiful

00:01:26.720 --> 00:01:28.879
illustration by Alison Horst.

00:01:28.879 --> 00:01:30.639
I was in my own little corner.

00:01:30.639 --> 00:01:32.519
I didn't know what I was doing.

00:01:32.519 --> 00:01:34.599
It felt like it was a lot of rainy days.

00:01:34.599 --> 00:01:39.680
And I was especially weighed down by the exclusivity I felt about data science.

00:01:39.680 --> 00:01:44.000
It felt like a tool that I was using, but it didn't feel like a community that I was

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:45.360
a part of.

00:01:45.360 --> 00:01:51.080
I was also weighed down by the historic exclusion of minority STEM professionals that I felt

00:01:51.080 --> 00:01:54.000
very much so in academia.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:59.599
And I also was stunned at the lack of action and support from my institution and from academia

00:01:59.599 --> 00:02:05.980
in general in the wake of a call for social justice and reform and equity in our field.

00:02:05.980 --> 00:02:08.440
And so, I lost my spark.

00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:11.679
It felt like I didn't know why I was in graduate school anymore.

00:02:11.679 --> 00:02:15.240
It felt like I didn't know why I was using these tools anymore.

00:02:15.240 --> 00:02:18.559
But open science saved me.

00:02:18.559 --> 00:02:21.279
It opened this landscape of community.

00:02:21.279 --> 00:02:24.880
It opened this opportunity for me to find myself again.

00:02:24.880 --> 00:02:28.440
And I found community in our studio and its users.

00:02:28.440 --> 00:02:34.880
I also participated in the OpenScape Champions program, and it changed my workflow radically.

00:02:34.880 --> 00:02:40.639
And I discovered, once again, my passion for data science education and also for engaging

00:02:40.639 --> 00:02:42.839
other students as well.

00:02:42.839 --> 00:02:46.880
And so, I may have said two words already that you're unfamiliar with, so I want to

00:02:46.880 --> 00:02:48.440
define them quickly.

00:02:48.440 --> 00:02:53.199
The first is open science, and the second is OpenScape.

00:02:53.199 --> 00:03:00.559
So open science is the tools and the practices that enable all of us to have more reproducible,

00:03:00.559 --> 00:03:04.839
transparent, and inclusive practices for data-intensive science.

00:03:04.839 --> 00:03:09.279
And so, when we're talking about tools, we're talking about these open source softwares

00:03:09.279 --> 00:03:13.240
and practices that we're using, for example, GitHub, and we talk about the practices as

00:03:13.240 --> 00:03:16.559
well and the communities that exist around these tools.

00:03:16.559 --> 00:03:18.960
For example, the RStudio community.

00:03:18.960 --> 00:03:22.720
And if you had the pleasure of hearing this morning's keynote, you learned a little bit

00:03:22.720 --> 00:03:24.360
about OpenScapes.

00:03:24.360 --> 00:03:29.720
And so, OpenScapes helps researchers reimagine data-intensive science and also to develop

00:03:29.720 --> 00:03:33.880
the skills to cultivate collaborative and inclusive teams.

00:03:33.880 --> 00:03:36.679
And they do that in two ways in particular.

00:03:36.679 --> 00:03:41.479
The first is through the OpenScapes Champions program, which I was a participant in, which

00:03:41.479 --> 00:03:45.639
is an open science mentorship program for science teams.

00:03:45.720 --> 00:03:50.360
And the second is through cultivating the OpenScapes mindset, which is a community-building

00:03:50.360 --> 00:03:54.080
framework to support the transition to open science.

00:03:54.080 --> 00:03:58.399
And it relies on these three principles that turn into a cycle of community building.

00:03:58.399 --> 00:04:04.039
The first is to empower research teams, the second is to amplify leaders, and the third

00:04:04.039 --> 00:04:06.600
is to engage mentors.

00:04:06.600 --> 00:04:11.440
And so, when I participated in the OpenScapes Champions program, it changed my life.

00:04:11.479 --> 00:04:16.640
I was so excited to see that new, beautiful landscape of open science and collaboration

00:04:16.640 --> 00:04:18.160
that existed.

00:04:18.160 --> 00:04:22.600
And so, I asked two questions after my participation in OpenScapes when we were checking in a few

00:04:22.600 --> 00:04:24.000
months later.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:28.640
The first was, why had I never heard of open science before?

00:04:28.640 --> 00:04:34.440
And the second was, how do I get more students like myself to learn about open science before

00:04:34.440 --> 00:04:37.600
they fall through the cracks in this pipeline?

00:04:37.600 --> 00:04:41.839
And so, that conversation, those questions, turned into a dialogue.

00:04:41.839 --> 00:04:47.720
And that dialogue has now turned into a long-term collaboration with OpenScapes to support and

00:04:47.720 --> 00:04:52.959
explore how we can support students from historically excluded backgrounds on their journeys to

00:04:52.959 --> 00:04:54.559
data science.

00:04:54.559 --> 00:05:00.579
And more than that, it also connected me with an incredible community of people similarly

00:05:00.579 --> 00:05:08.779
motivated by their values, by valuing diversity, inclusion, transparency, and collaboration.

00:05:08.779 --> 00:05:13.420
And so, I was all of a sudden exposed to all of these incredible resources, especially

00:05:13.420 --> 00:05:18.640
the RStudio community, and I learned what it had to offer.

00:05:18.640 --> 00:05:23.899
And so, I went from an outsider and believing that data science was just a tool that I used

00:05:23.899 --> 00:05:29.220
to do my work, to now being a participant in the change that I'm hoping to see in our

00:05:29.220 --> 00:05:32.399
data science communities.

00:05:32.399 --> 00:05:37.140
And so, when we've been reflecting about how I made it to this point and how I'm standing

00:05:37.140 --> 00:05:41.660
in front of you all today, I thought about a formula for the success that's led to this

00:05:41.660 --> 00:05:42.820
point.

00:05:42.820 --> 00:05:45.859
The first point being, values in action.

00:05:45.859 --> 00:05:49.299
The second, being investment aligned with these values.

00:05:49.299 --> 00:05:53.220
And the third, being an OpenScapes mindset at all levels.

00:05:53.220 --> 00:05:56.660
And I'll take a moment to go into each of these.

00:05:56.660 --> 00:05:58.859
The first is values in action.

00:05:58.859 --> 00:06:04.579
It was incredibly refreshing for me to participate and be a part of communities that showed me

00:06:04.579 --> 00:06:06.820
that they were walking their talk.

00:06:06.820 --> 00:06:12.339
Not only is inclusivity and transparency and collaboration a part of the work that RStudio

00:06:12.339 --> 00:06:16.980
is doing, but it's also a part of the community and the people who are a part of it.

00:06:16.980 --> 00:06:21.619
Some examples of that include my R users and R ladies.

00:06:21.619 --> 00:06:27.019
Also, being able to see and experience the authentic leadership within the open science

00:06:27.019 --> 00:06:28.019
community.

00:06:28.019 --> 00:06:30.820
In particular, with OpenScapes and RStudio.

00:06:30.820 --> 00:06:34.700
We've had the chance to hear from so many of the incredible developers and leaders who

00:06:34.700 --> 00:06:36.260
are part of these teams.

00:06:36.260 --> 00:06:40.820
And it's refreshing to see how open they are, to hearing our concerns, how much a part of

00:06:40.820 --> 00:06:42.700
they are a part of this community.

00:06:42.700 --> 00:06:45.660
And it matters that all of us are working together.

00:06:45.660 --> 00:06:48.940
And lastly, action with a sense of urgency.

00:06:48.940 --> 00:06:52.660
I don't think any of us would be here today if we didn't believe the RStudio community

00:06:52.660 --> 00:06:55.420
was going to make this a safe place.

00:06:56.100 --> 00:07:00.859
An example of that is the code of conduct and COVID policies for this conference.

00:07:00.859 --> 00:07:03.899
This is my very first time giving a non-academic talk.

00:07:03.899 --> 00:07:08.140
This is my very first time talking about diversity and equity.

00:07:08.140 --> 00:07:10.179
And that's very scary for me.

00:07:10.179 --> 00:07:16.019
But I knew that the place that I wanted to do it for the first time was at RStudio conference.

00:07:16.019 --> 00:07:21.500
And that, to me, is a testament to what this community is capable of.

00:07:21.500 --> 00:07:24.859
The next is investing in those community values.

00:07:24.859 --> 00:07:28.459
And I think that there are two ways that the open science community has demonstrated

00:07:28.459 --> 00:07:30.579
this to me in particular.

00:07:30.579 --> 00:07:36.100
And the first is prioritizing, compensating people for their time, their effort, and their

00:07:36.100 --> 00:07:39.500
contributions to safer spaces for all of us.

00:07:39.500 --> 00:07:43.859
My work with Openscapes was the very first time in my career of working on diversity,

00:07:43.859 --> 00:07:48.859
equity, and inclusion in over six years where I was compensated for the work that I was doing.

00:07:48.859 --> 00:07:53.899
And to me, it made me less stressed that this was a side project that I was passionate about

00:07:53.940 --> 00:07:57.619
and showed me that I could prioritize this in my life and that it was a priority to the

00:07:57.619 --> 00:07:59.859
community that I was serving as well.

00:07:59.859 --> 00:08:01.859
And it made all the difference.

00:08:01.859 --> 00:08:06.579
The next is lowering the barriers for participation and engagement.

00:08:06.579 --> 00:08:10.700
The reason I'm standing before you all today is that I'm a participant in the RStudio Diversity

00:08:10.700 --> 00:08:15.700
Scholars Program that made it possible for me to be here and to participate in workshops

00:08:15.700 --> 00:08:16.899
and present to you all today.

00:08:16.899 --> 00:08:22.940
And I think it's just one example of the many ways that RStudio community is committed to

00:08:22.940 --> 00:08:27.940
making sure that we get a lot of people in these rooms having these conversations.

00:08:27.940 --> 00:08:32.460
Additionally, the resource guides and the openness of this community to learners at

00:08:32.460 --> 00:08:37.659
every level is an incredible asset to being able to bring people from all types of backgrounds

00:08:37.659 --> 00:08:39.700
into our data science communities.

00:08:39.700 --> 00:08:43.419
I think a great example of that is if you've ever, you know, been searching for the answer

00:08:43.419 --> 00:08:49.380
to a question that you have, you've probably stumbled upon the RStudio blog as well.

00:08:49.380 --> 00:08:52.739
And lastly is the Openscapes mindset at all levels.

00:08:53.539 --> 00:08:55.940
As I mentioned, there are three tiers to this flywheel.

00:08:55.940 --> 00:08:58.299
The first is empowering research teams.

00:08:58.299 --> 00:09:00.539
The second being amplifying leaders.

00:09:00.539 --> 00:09:03.059
And the third being engaged mentors.

00:09:03.059 --> 00:09:07.979
And ultimately, what this is building is a community where at every level, regardless

00:09:07.979 --> 00:09:13.419
of hierarchy or leadership structure, that all of us are committed to building community.

00:09:13.419 --> 00:09:17.700
All of us are committed to mentoring and working with one another.

00:09:17.700 --> 00:09:23.820
And ultimately, we're able to build collaboration and mentorship not only within our organizations,

00:09:23.820 --> 00:09:25.419
but beyond.

00:09:25.419 --> 00:09:31.260
It makes our work more collaborative, more inclusive, it makes it kinder, and more efficient

00:09:31.260 --> 00:09:32.820
as well.

00:09:32.820 --> 00:09:38.900
And ultimately, building community with the Openscapes mindset means that you're not alone.

00:09:38.900 --> 00:09:43.820
Regardless of if you just joined the team or you're well into your work, this is a way

00:09:43.820 --> 00:09:46.739
for us to collaborate and learn with one another.

00:09:46.739 --> 00:09:50.580
And no one has to try to fix anything by themselves.

00:09:50.580 --> 00:09:56.859
And we can all experience and enjoy the landscape Open Science has to offer.

00:09:56.859 --> 00:09:59.820
So what does it look like when we do the work?

00:09:59.820 --> 00:10:03.280
What does it look like when all of these principles are in place?

00:10:03.280 --> 00:10:06.659
What does it look like when we put this formula together?

00:10:06.659 --> 00:10:12.099
Values in action, investment aligned with these values, and lastly, an Openscapes mindset

00:10:12.099 --> 00:10:14.700
at all levels.

00:10:14.700 --> 00:10:18.140
It looks like going from learner to teacher.

00:10:18.140 --> 00:10:24.700
This is a photo of me teaching my very first Open Science lecture to a cohort of Openscapes

00:10:24.700 --> 00:10:28.780
champions that participated after I did.

00:10:28.780 --> 00:10:33.619
It looks like expanding our open data and open principles to communities beyond our

00:10:33.619 --> 00:10:34.619
own.

00:10:34.619 --> 00:10:38.619
And I was able to host an event in other communities that I'm a part of.

00:10:38.619 --> 00:10:43.539
This year, I hosted in a data science mixer for Black and Marine Science, another organization

00:10:43.539 --> 00:10:45.140
that I'm a member of.

00:10:45.140 --> 00:10:50.179
And I was able to bring together quantitative marine scientists to build community and talk

00:10:50.179 --> 00:10:54.979
about Open Science and explore how we can collaborate with one another.

00:10:54.979 --> 00:10:59.820
And lastly, it looks like building the better future that we want to see.

00:10:59.820 --> 00:11:05.380
This is from my colleague and I being recipients of the Code for Science and Society event

00:11:05.380 --> 00:11:10.820
fund grant, where in the spring of 2023, we're going to be bringing a Pathways to Open Science

00:11:10.820 --> 00:11:15.380
programming to students from Historically Black Colleges and Universities, HBCUs, of

00:11:15.380 --> 00:11:18.979
which I am an alum.

00:11:18.979 --> 00:11:27.659
Thank you.

00:11:27.659 --> 00:11:33.859
And so all of that to say that a more equitable future for our field is possible.

00:11:33.859 --> 00:11:36.099
But it's time for us to do the work.

00:11:36.099 --> 00:11:40.340
And so I'm leaving everyone in this room today with three action items and three ways

00:11:40.340 --> 00:11:43.260
to begin those conversations.

00:11:43.260 --> 00:11:48.859
And the first is to center the voices of those we work to support and include.

00:11:48.859 --> 00:11:50.760
This is a time to listen.

00:11:50.760 --> 00:11:53.020
This is a time to amplify.

00:11:53.020 --> 00:11:56.700
It's not a time to do anything more than that.

00:11:56.700 --> 00:12:02.099
Also, to ask hard questions in the rooms where you do have a voice.

00:12:02.099 --> 00:12:07.539
Look at your organization, at your hiring structure, at your onboarding process, and

00:12:07.539 --> 00:12:09.900
ask yourself some of those questions.

00:12:09.900 --> 00:12:12.260
Where are people falling through the cracks?

00:12:12.260 --> 00:12:14.739
Where can we do better?

00:12:14.739 --> 00:12:20.900
What needs to happen for our team to include everyone at any level?

00:12:20.900 --> 00:12:27.619
And lastly, be the community member who you want to meet at the beginning of your journey.

00:12:27.619 --> 00:12:31.820
Had I not met Julie, I would not be standing in front of you all today.

00:12:31.820 --> 00:12:35.859
And so I encourage you all to be a Julie.

00:12:35.859 --> 00:12:41.859
And also to continue to perpetuate community and provide this inclusive space at every

00:12:41.859 --> 00:12:47.580
level of leadership, at every level of engagement, so that no matter what angle someone enters

00:12:47.580 --> 00:12:53.739
our RStudio community at or enters the data science community at, that they feel included

00:12:53.739 --> 00:12:57.820
and that we're ready to work together.

00:12:57.820 --> 00:13:04.260
And so while I stand before you all today as one of few, I strongly believe that leveraging

00:13:04.260 --> 00:13:08.419
our community, I can be one of many.

00:13:08.419 --> 00:13:12.580
And with that, I would like to sincerely thank and acknowledge everyone who made presenting

00:13:12.580 --> 00:13:13.979
in front of you all today possible.

00:13:13.979 --> 00:13:17.340
So I'd like to thank Julie and the OpenScapes team.

00:13:17.340 --> 00:13:19.979
I'd like to thank the RStudio diversity scholars.

00:13:19.979 --> 00:13:24.260
And I would also like to thank Mackay Floyd and my support system, who made sure, even

00:13:24.260 --> 00:13:31.260
though I just took my PhD comprehensive exams last week, and I passed, that I was still...

00:13:31.260 --> 00:13:33.260
Thank you.

00:13:33.260 --> 00:13:35.260
Thank you.

00:13:35.260 --> 00:13:37.260
Thank you.

00:13:37.260 --> 00:13:44.140
That I was still able and ready to be standing in front of you all today and give this presentation.

00:13:44.140 --> 00:13:47.059
And so with that, I'm happy to take any questions.

00:13:47.059 --> 00:13:48.619
I'd love to connect with you all.

00:13:48.619 --> 00:13:50.700
I'd love to work with you all.

00:13:50.700 --> 00:13:52.580
And I'm ready to take any questions.

00:13:52.580 --> 00:13:53.580
Thank you.

00:13:53.580 --> 00:13:54.580
Thank you.

00:13:54.580 --> 00:13:54.580


